Spectacular jump in "wingsuit" over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped Thursday from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination equipped with wings), it rose to 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate shrine, located at more than 3,000 metres above sea level, where many badauds had gathered to observe its feat.
A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners find it difficult to find the money to repair the road infrastructure in decrepitude, many people are looking for a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself above the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which records all the miles driven by a motorist and transmits the information to officials, are at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in the planning government offices to redesign the outdated system of financing the major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of major axis planning suddenly sparked a lively debate and heated alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and eventually the road on which you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is down.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already embarked these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly essential for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will start recording the miles travelled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not tenable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative," he said.
Wunks calls this a mileage user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious laws on global warming.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chair of the House of Representatives Transport Committee, said he also saw it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation's free market also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
"It's not just a tax coming into a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, vice-president of politics at Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment per mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several States and major cities are making progress on their part.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's largest experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometric fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is trying a trial on a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the American east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their every move.
"Anxiety about Big Brother and this kind of thing is a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management in Nevada's Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned at its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices."
It is not necessary to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and comings.
Nevada is one of a few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Researching this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California start-up named True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to break into the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have pleased major axis planners because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Great mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less costly ways and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are looking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "driving payment" insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Car drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them," said a paper on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on mile payment is not simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's Director of Legislation and Public Affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listeners
The English musician hasn't finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, it concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone pantois.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he had declared that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than a lap in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke has planned to re-release this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, unpublished studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and pouches, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a foretaste of his new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and a cleverly mastered rock electricity.
New ones already on the listener list
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal her charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a light cavalcade that gradually slows down to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John's Rocket Man or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in any case in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
Guitar riffs, bewitching, make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun in any case playing chameleon with these titles: informant turns, man aboard a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at once, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
Nothing surprising that he had a mask in his hand in the photograph of the campaign L'Invitation au Voyage, by the Louis Vuitton brand, whose new face he embodied.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that injured soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers prior to their return to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr.Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured members - who do not meet the "universal service" rule of the army requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for pension benefits.
In particular, they cited two cases reported by La Presse canadienne, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the military despite his request to stay another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case followed that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before being ready because he did not meet the rule of universality of service.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that it was totally different than wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse canadienne on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of the major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has struggled to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not fit for combat.
Under the current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for overseas deployments, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the length of service required to obtain pension benefits.
Liberal veteran spokesman Jim Karygiannis asked Wednesday for Corporal Hawkins' reinstatement, while New Democratic Jack Harris called for the immediate end of "this shameful practice".
Disney bets on the tablets to launch an animated series
The American media and entertainment group Disney decided to favor tablets over its own television channels for the upcoming release of a new children's series.
The first nine episodes of Sheriff Callie's Wild West will be available from November 24 on watchdisneyjunior.com or via its phone and tablet app.
Its worldwide launch on Disney's channels is not expected until 2014, details the press release of its Disney Junior division.
The cartoon, intended for children aged 2 to 7, tells the adventures of the pussy Callie, sheriff of a city in the American west where she makes order with a magic lasso.
Each episode includes two 11-minute stories.
"Interacting with smartphones and tablets is a second nature for children today," commented Albert Cheng, Vice President for Digital Products at Disney/ABC Television Group, quoted in the press release.
This type of experience is part of Disney's efforts to "extend the lifespan of its series and build new relationships with its audience through increasingly important digital platforms," he added.
A survey published earlier this week by Common Sense Media showed an explosion in the use of mobile devices by young children in the United States: 38% of those under 2 years of age have already used a tablet or phone, and 72% of those under 8 years of age, compared to 10% and 38% respectively two years ago.
Snowden is ready to "cooperate" with Germany on the issue of US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the U.S. intelligence informant, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers on their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met on Thursday with Mr Snowden in Russia, where he enjoys the right to asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter that the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, Mr Snowden said, "Although the result of my efforts was obviously positive, my government continues to treat the difference of opinion as a leak and seeks to penalize political discourse with accusations against which it is impossible to defend itself."
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop the criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with spying and stealing state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, German Interior Minister, told the Zeit Online: "If Mr Snowden is ready to talk to German officials, we will make this possible."
Relations between the United States and Germany were strained by complaints that the NSA had tapped the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the deputy who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the foreign secret services, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness "without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the United States," it was necessary to take advantage of it.
Mr Ströbele, a German Green MEP, published a photo of him with Mr Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that, according to the lawyer of the former NSA consultant, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Mr Snowden was testifying in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be "safe" there, said the MP.
Mr. Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been subjected to a "serious and sustained" persecution campaign that forced him to leave his country.
However, he said he had been encouraged by the global reaction to “my act of political expression”.
Citizens around the world as well as senior officials – including in the United States – considered the revelation of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance to be of public benefit.
The letter puts forward an offer of cooperation with the German authorities "when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved".
Cogeco Cable could soon offer interactive TV
Cogeco Cable subscribers may well have access to applications such as Facebook, Twitter and ultimately the Netflix video-on-demand service via their television in a future that does not seem so far away.
Cogeco's subsidiary indicated on Thursday that it is currently conducting preliminary testing of the beta version of this platform with some of its users.
"This will allow us to highlight more user-friendly interfaces as well as more options," explained Cogeco's President and CEO, Louis Audet, in an interview.
Cogeco Cable is thus following in the footsteps of its competitors, such as Bell, even though Cogeco's subsidiary does not yet have a specific date for this new platform.
"We need to adapt and change or resist change and fail," said Audet.
The ultimate goal remains to provide tools that our clients do not currently have access to.
The Rogers telecommunications giant has already indicated that it could offer Netflix if certain technical details, which have not been cited, could be resolved.
In the United States, the popular video service claims to be in discussions with some major cable companies to make its service available via their broadcast platforms.
Cogeco and Cogeco Cable also welcomed the announcement made by the Harper government in its Speech from the Throne on October 16.
Ottawa wants to force cable and satellite television providers to offer customers the opportunity to pay for pay-per-view services.
"It's been about two and a half years since we've been saying that the idea of forcing consumers to buy large chain packages doesn't work," said Audet.
He hopes, however, that the consultations conducted by the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) will lead to interesting recommendations.
"A new kind of frame of reference will have to emerge from these discussions to define our new Canadian cultural policy with respect to television," said Cogeco's CEO.
The CRTC has been consulting with the public since last week and is expected to continue with the industry next spring.
On the results side, Cogeco reported a net profit of $43.8 million in the fourth quarter, or 82¢ per share.
This is a decrease from the net profit of 44.9 million, or 83¢ per share, for the same period last year.
The Montreal-based company explains this decline by amortization costs related to new acquisitions.
Cogeco acquired the US-based Atlantic Broadband cable company for $1.36 billion in 2012.
This was the company's first major acquisition after the one that failed in Portugal.
Last December, the Montréal company also purchased Peer 1 Network Entreprises, an Internet provider based in Vancouver, for $526 million.
As for Cogeco's revenues, they grew by 41.5% in the fourth quarter to reach 504.7 million.
They are $1.8 billion for the current fiscal year.
The net profit of its main subsidiary, Cogeco Cable, was 43.9 million, or 90¢ per share, down from 45.7 million, or 93¢ per share, of the same period last year.
However, Cogeco Cable's revenues increased by 45% to $470.4 million.
The company lost 15,237 customers in the fourth quarter.
However, for the 2013 fiscal year, the number of Cogeco Cable customers is on the rise 5,546.
Mr. Audet is not concerned that the number of clients fluctuates in this way.
For me, this is not an indication of a change in trend, he observed.
It varies from quarter to quarter with very strong competition.
Horses in beef products
Horse meat was detected in cans of beef products, sold by two small UK retail chains at low prices, today announced the food hygiene agency.
Routine tests revealed that the products, developed in January in Romania and sold by the Home Bargains and Quality Save chains, contained horse DNA of 1 to 5%.
"Since horse meat is not mentioned in the list of ingredients, it should not have been present in the product," explained the UK agency.
A scandal about the presence of horse meat in cooked dishes broke out in Europe at the beginning of the year, following tests carried out in Ireland.
According to reviews by the European Commission, France has been the country most affected by the presence of this type of meat in products intended to contain only beef.
A collision between two vehicles injured four, early Friday, on Highway 131, in Lanaudière.
Shortly before 4 a.m., a motorist who was travelling in a northerly direction in Saint-Félix-de-Valois lost control of his vehicle and struck a car that was coming in the other direction.
The four occupants of both vehicles were injured, but there was no fear for their lives.
