Frontier Airlines plans to charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers carrying carry-on-flight baggage for up to $100.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in her announcement on Wednesday, she indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them down the plane.
New hand luggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free of charge.
Frontier stated that it would charge $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if travellers paid only once at the boarding gate.
Frontier's spokesperson, Kate O'Malley, indicated that the $100 was provided to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to charge that price," she explained.
The airlines started charging for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these costs put as many things as they could in the carry-on baggage stowed in the upper compartments, so there was often no more room in these compartments.
These charges are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It is a question of making the most loyal Frontier customers understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their ticket from the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger queued at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand baggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often frown about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people in Wall Street view the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
However, many of them did not receive the cost of baggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first hand baggage charges three years ago, and the low-cost Allegiant company followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant to airlines Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the surcharge charges.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's carry-on baggage charges were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate as passengers discovered the company's unusual carry-on charges.
"I've never seen such a fluid boarding procedure in my entire professional career," he said.
I expected to see a gnash of teeth and a fight breaking out at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers boarded at the speed of lightning."
Frontier also does as Spirit and charges $2 for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be refreshed free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but returned back seven months after passengers complained and while no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for carry-on baggage when passengers do not purchase their tickets directly from the airline is its last effort to encourage customers to go to its site.
Airlines pay online travel vendors like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of going to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half a mile of loyalty to customers who bought their ticket via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she reduced mile bonuses by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile border trip purchased from an online travel agency would earn 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they buy their ticket directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in its home town, Denver, but its business is shrinking and it is losing money.
Revenues fell by 9% and its flight capacity decreased by almost 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to straighten Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
The NSA calls into question an "internal error" and not hackers for the breakdown of its site
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said on Friday that it was a bug that caused the breakdown of its public site for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed online.
"NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update," the spy agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service attack [DSD] are false.
Earlier tonight, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been broken down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "not at all" compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesperson explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactics is not very sophisticated and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The once ultra-secret NSA, a time dubbed the "No Such Agency", has found itself in the spotlight and heavily criticized in recent months following a wave of revelations about its extensive national and foreign communications surveillance programs – which are part of the NSA's secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by former disillusioned NSA consultant Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has caused a lot of speculation that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
Delta City Centre now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed on Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found a new job.
Delta promises not to let down its employees.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, and employees were met individually to assess their needs.
"This support will continue for the next six months," explains Delta Hotels Regional Director of Labour Relations, Félix Bisson.
The Delta is closed in a highly competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned this building had choices to make.
Either he was reinvesting in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that appeared in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that's what happened," explains Paul Arsenault, Chair of Tourism Transat at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other hotels in Montreal will also be converted in the coming months, such as the Crown Plaza, which will become a residence for seniors.
Meanwhile, four hotel projects totalling nearly 600 rooms will be launched in two years.
For Titan's CEO, "Goodyear Amiens buys project starts with zero employee"
After throwing out the towel in January for the partial takeover of Amiens-Nord's Goodyear site promised at the closure, Maurice Taylor, the CEO of the American tiremaker Titan, declares, today, ready to save 333 jobs out of the plant's 1,137.
Arnaud Montebourg, Minister for Productive Recovery, had already announced it on Monday 21 October.
After giving up the plan to buy the plant in January, you come back today.
You had uttered violent attacks and insults, speaking of "so-called workers", who "work three hours" a day, "crazy" unions, targeting the CGT.
We don't understand that volte-face.
Is it to please Mr. Montebourg?
I'm not trying to please anyone.
Except for my wife.
Mr Montebourg, is a charming young man who is trying to save some of the best paid industrial jobs.
If I hurt someone with my words, I'm sorry.
But France also has a high level of tax and unemployment.
Does the truth hurt you?
Working seven hours a day when working eight hours in other countries handicaps France.
In India, China and many other countries, we work ten to twelve hours a day.
But I have no prejudices about France.
What I see is a factory that makes good agricultural tires, has good equipment, is well located and has space to expand.
Why does Titan need this factory so much?
Titan doesn't need to buy this factory.
But, with a proper price and skilled workers, it's worth trying.
What kind of deal do you expect between the CGT and Goodyear?
If, since the plant's closure was announced, Goodyear had offered employees a good severance pay, I think 100% of employees would have accepted it.
Now, let's imagine Titan buys Goodyear's closed plant.
As a result, Titan could move the machines to Poland or to any other EU country that still has its own currency.
I think Mr Montebourg knows that.
But he wants to keep the Amiens factory with at least 333 well-paid jobs.
Titan agrees to recruit them from around 1,200 current Goodyear employees.
So Mr. Montebourg needs a commitment from Titan before he tries to get the CGT to sit at the table with Goodyear.
The first step is for the CGT and Goodyear to seal an agreement on severance benefits for all employees.
As a result, there will be no more employees in the plant.
Mr Montebourg said you were ready to guarantee these 333 jobs for four years.
Do you confirm that?
The only number I mentioned to the minister is 333.
I know he'd like a four-year guarantee.
But, as I told you, the CGT and Goodyear must first agree on severance benefits.
If all employees accept them, the plant's purchase plan starts with zero employees.
How can we give job duration guarantees when there are no more employees left on the site?
If Mr. Montebourg manages to get the CGT and Goodyear to agree and Titan buys the plant, we intend to stay in North Amiens for more than four years.
Bombardier's profit declines, as aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in net earnings on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and aircraft deliveries during the third quarter and contractual problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not provide in-flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September.
After the inaugural flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the test aircraft flew only three times, and the question then arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
The results were not in line with the forecast and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from "overperformance" to "sector performance" due to the low potential for the stock exchange to increase in the next quarter or two quarters.
"Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed with the profit margin in the Transport division," Cameron Doerksen said in a memo to customers.
We expect Bombardier to register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it into the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and first flew in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft is so far modest at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's assertions about the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
Currently, the company has registered a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and CEO, is confident that Bombardier will meet its target of 300 firm orders prior to the commercial launch of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing according to schedule.
"The test aircraft did not remain on the ground for longer than expected," said Mr. Beaudoin at a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned during the aircraft's shutdown time.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to make a first flight and provide an update period, and that's what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, while the others will follow shortly thereafter, the company said.
However, analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its inaugural flight.
