The lawyer went back home, found out about the drugs, and they called nine times.
The court heard that Ditta was a "regular user" of cocaine after tests showed traces of this class A drug in her hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied using cocaine. He stated that he had spoken to the alleged drug dealer because he was his client and argued that their discussions were subject to a "legal privilege".
During his arrest, Ditta picked up his wallet and attempted to remove several credit cards, but they were all seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During an interrogation, he stated that he owned an office at his home, as well as at his place of work, and that he was sometimes called home by clients for legal matters.
