But in its opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA stated that it "had never had to deal with a problem of sexual assault on children within its organization."
Director General Phillip Hare was questioned about two cases: an employee of the YMCA was charged with child pornography offences and a physical education instructor of the YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual assault on children in the centre where he worked in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, counsel to the Commission, that he had been aware of the first case but that he was not aware of the second.
He also admitted that the YMCA's opening statement was inaccurate by pointing out, "external controls of the YMCA were carried out and indicated that the safety of children was a top priority for the organization."
