Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had shown that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that, in man, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies with other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
It probably won't take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to tamper with the movement of the tail and present it as going further left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail drifting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you encounter other dogs repeatedly and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine Behavior John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, indicated that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that the dogs were turning their heads to the left when they were looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, "The dogs were more easily going to a robot dog when its tail was moving to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
"Although there are many elements from different mammals that indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
