A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for scientific mission to the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised at the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin?
This is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
If in the past the species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in science of species classification.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being questioned due to advances in genetics.
Similarly, two very morphologically close species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has stated?
From a conservation perspective, knowledge of these genetic differences is essential to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
While this population had long been known to researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if there is a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than with a local disappearance of a population of a species that is more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the possibility of recovery from nearby stocks.
With respect to the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new discovered species has emerged, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This brewing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on searching for life on other planets than on marine research and it is high time it changed.
RBS suspends two traders on the foreign exchange market
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange market division according to two sources close to the file, again showing that the regulators' global investigation into suspicions of currency market manipulations is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in investigations into the world's largest financial market, where US$5.3 trillion change hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expansion of the investigation that echoes the scandal of manipulations of the Libor interbank rate.
The bank, which refused to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
"The ongoing investigation into this matter is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators," said a bank representative two weeks ago.
Last month, sources close to the file stated that RBS had sent instant email and message files to and from a former trader, to the British regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European cash trading manager for currency at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, the European head of cash exchange trading at Citi, was laid off this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and from bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, added sources close to the file.
UBS explained this week that it had brought an action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator, Finma, stated that it was investigating suspicions of foreign exchange market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
Around the world, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are examining allegations about bankers who have agreed to manipulate rates in the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Crédit Suisse also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, reported sources close to the file.
Banks peel instant messages and emails sent for years to find cases of wrongdoing.
News about these investigations has rocked traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest engines of growth of investment bank trading units in recent years, but that has been questioned this year due to low currency volatility that limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to minimize the case by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast, highly liquid foreign exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
A senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange transactions, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading platforms and the increasingly frequent use by banks of their own internal platforms "explains that it is possible to start having an impact on the market at little cost."
The news came the same day Credit Suisse announced that it had sent a trader working in its London Stock Exchange trading office this week after it caused a $6 million loss at the end of last year.
The bank promptly informed the competent authorities and cooperated with regulators.
"We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the case has been mastered," said a representative of Crédit Suisse.
