After hundreds of thousands of people received notices of termination from their claimants, Republicans criticized the president in the past few days by accusing him of cheating on the American people.
Yesterday, Barack Obama adjusted his original promise.
"The vast majority of people with health insurance that suits them can keep it," he said in a speech in Boston.
Speaking of what he calls "an effervescence in the news" about the terminations, President Obama prompted the Americans who received these notices to seek new insurance on the market.
Most people will be able to obtain comprehensive and better-adapted health plans for the same price, even less expensive than expected.
"You'll get away with it," he said.
The Administration has announced that it is not surprising that the 5% of the population who are self-insured are forced to change their plans because their coverage does not meet the new standards required under the Affordable Care Act.
"Let me speak directly to these Americans: you deserve better," said Kathleen Sebelius in her testimony before the Committee on Energy and Trade in Washington.
Ms. Sebelius, who oversees the implementation of the Affordable Care Act, said that the October launch of the online market had failed "unfortunately".
"I'm as frustrated and irritated as anyone," she added.
I can't wait to regain your trust.
It was an exasperated Kathleen Sebelius who uttered this sentence, while she believed her microphone cut, speaking to an assistant sitting behind her at yesterday's Assembly session following a contentious exchange of views with Billy Long, Missouri Republican Representative, to determine whether she should adhere to the Obamacare.
For more than three hours, Billy Long kept insistently asking Ms.Sebelius why the "architect" of the Affordable Care Act had not voluntarily renounced government-sponsored insurance to subscribe to a plan via HealthCare.gov, which she now boasts to millions of Americans.
Vettel and a special helmet in Abu Dhabi
The lucky one, Jake Vite Prekop, combined the colours of the car brand and the German flag, while integrating the notions of speed and heat at the level of the track.
Germany's Sebastian Vettel, four-time Formula One world champion, took part in the free practice of the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix on Friday in a special helmet designed by a 21-year-old Mexican fan.
Vettel has chosen among 1,500 drawings sent from all over the world, as part of a competition launched by one of the sponsors, an automobile brand, of his stable.
He was invited to follow Abu Dhabi's GP, with a friend, and can thus see the German champion closely, on the track and in his stand.
Vettel was supposed to be wearing this helmet on Friday and Saturday at the test.
It is likely that he will have another special helmet Sunday, for the race, intended to mark his 4th consecutive world title.
A resident of Aubervilliers launches his Suburban Party
Let's not be mistaken.
In the spirit of Abdel-Malik Djermoune, its founder, the "Suburbarian Party" is not only aimed at the suburbs.
I have chosen a map of France as a logo, he justifies.
When I speak of the suburbs, I speak to all those who are excluded from the great national family.
However, his project, presented on Thursday in a press conference in his native commune of Aubervilliers, was born of the desire to better defend multiculturalism, this great cultural melting pot that characterizes above all the neighborhoods.
My proposal #1 is to create a ministry of multiculturalism, he says.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune, 50, a territorial attaché, claims today to be "100% apolitical" even though he has not always been neutral.
Militant in 2002 alongside Jean-Pierre Chevénement, he then locally supported Dominique de Villepin between 2010 and 2011.
I know that the values of equality that I advocate in my program are linked to the left, but if the right-wingers are ready to support me, I will also listen to them, he continues.
Only extremist parties I don't talk about.
In addition to multiculturalism, Abdel-Malik Djermoune has built his programme - accessible on the Internet - based on many themes that are supposed to speak to the inhabitants of the suburbs and in particular to young people: the right to vote for foreigners, the legalization of cannabis, the civil majority at the age of 16, the rehabilitation of the function of building keeper...
It remains to be found candidates to form lists and defend his ideas on the political scene."For the 2014 municipal elections, this risks being fair," he admits.
It's a matter of time and money.
The Suburban Party should still be represented in Aubervilliers through my candidacy and I also hope in other cities.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune has already seven lists in metropolitan France and Martinique.
"And the support emails I've received since yesterday don't all come from the suburbs," he rejoices.
John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage "had gone too far inappropriately"
John Kerry indicated a softening of the United States' defensive attitude to its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions spying "had gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he had, like Barack Obama, ruled on "autopilot" when a series of incendiary revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities came into being.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 11 September."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed boundaries, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said, "In some cases, it went too far inappropriately."
And the Speaker is determined to try to clarify and clarify to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels mistaken.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused as part of this process.
Mr. Kerry stressed, however, that NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added, "We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. legislators will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the U.S.," said the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European Affairs on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut indicated that he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and that he was concerned about the threats they had made regarding a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the sense of frustration with the surveillance of the National Security Agency.
"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain at our side in the mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate Sub-Committee on European Affairs, in an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to combat terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some of the US allies, but the agency's director said this week that it was inaccurate and that this was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations referred to documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of State.
The Director of Intelligence Services, James Clapper, justified the spying of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumult atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a Congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy stated that the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show "affective firmness."
He explained that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the kind of spying programmes they have been implementing for years.
"We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they must also understand that we are not the only ones in the world who do spying," said Murphy.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry has planned to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to manage the rancour generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as United States surveillance activities.
