Australian woman appeals her sentence of imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident, sentenced to 15 days' imprisonment in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the judgment and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Province Court on June 15 of false statements after telling the Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance recordings later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interviewed Bamford for two days before she confessed to inventing the story of all parts.
She was detained in a cell at the local police station before the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days' imprisonment in a low-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women's prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian Rugby League player Peter Tunks, who appealed to Canberra's Foreign Department to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
"We have obviously had a distressing moment, but we hope to take her home safely as soon as possible," said Tunks.
Bamford appealed the judgment and was released after bailing 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on vacation in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources reported that Bamford was represented by a local lawyer from Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to an increased sentence of up to two years' imprisonment and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder in Phuket of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore her deteriorated image to tourists, which could lead to acquittal.
The French police will arrest Anderlecht's supporters who came other than with the RSCA buses.
The French police decided to set strict rules regarding the meeting of the Royal Sporting Club d'Anderlecht against the Paris Saint-Germain scheduled for Tuesday, Marie Verbeke, the spokesperson for the Brussels-midi police zone, said on Friday.
Belgian fans of the RSCA who wish to go to this meeting of the Champions League will have to use the travel system set up by the RSCA.
"The bus convoy will be escorted by police from a former Rekem border post to the PSG stadium," the spokesman said.
The process will be the same for the return.
"If other supporters intend to travel to Paris by other means, the French police prefecture has indicated that measures have been taken to make it possible to make arrests or even police custody," said Marie Verbeke.
Living together in French, the challenge of the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of students have a mother tongue other than French.
One year ago, this prompted a consultation with parents, students, teachers and education staff to consider how to better integrate students who live on horseback between different cultures.
The school board has just unveiled its vision of "Living Together in French".
Vision diversité has been walking around schools for the past year to help students of all backgrounds discover common landmarks that are not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighbourhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Big names of writers, artists, whether they're ethnic or they've come from somewhere else.
Who are our builders?
"So, we create projects so that they identify with all of this," explains Vision diversity president Aïda Kamar.
Michel Venne of the New World Institute identified several challenges for the school board.
"On the transmission, for example, of what Quebec culture is, the sense of belonging, the support of the staff in the transformations we are experiencing, within the student clientele," he lists.
The Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board has created a research centre that will give tools to teachers who also sometimes come from elsewhere.
Rachida Azdouz of the University of Montreal will be its Scientific Director.
Preparing to manage a class in a North American, Quebec context.
"Different teaching strategies, that's the real need," she sums up.
Research will focus on inclusion from all angles: linguistic, academic, social and cultural.
